<subSubSection box="[356,551,279,305]" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="37.[347,560,279,338]" box="[356,551,279,305]" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">Macronaria indet.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="718" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="37.[347,560,279,338]" box="[347,560,311,338]" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">
(
<figureCitation box="[356,434,311,337]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="35.[132,143,1895,1912]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@35.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIG. 24. — Sauropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-D, posterior left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG11-837) in labial (A), mesial (B), lingual (C) and distal (D) views; E-H, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R905) in labial (E), mesial (F), lingual (G) and distal (H) views; I-L, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG13-2330) in labial (I), mesial (J), lingual (K) and distal (L) views; M-P, left premaxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-R289) in labial (M), mesial (N), lingual (O) and distal (P) views; Q-T, dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-3495) in labial (Q), mesial (R), lingual (S) and distal (T) views; U-X, left dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14- R435) in labial (U), mesial (V), lingual (W) and distal (X) views; Y-AA, maxillary tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANG R-1732) in labial (Y), distal (Z) and lingual (AA) views. Scale bar: A-X, 2 cm; Y-AA, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902095/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">Figs 24</figureCitation>
Y-AA; 25A)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[130,776,375,1103]" box="[132,272,375,401]" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[130,776,375,1103]" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">
In addition to the turiasaur, a second sauropod taxon may be present at Angeac-Charente site. It is only represented by a single abraded tooth and a tooth recovered from microremains (
<figureCitation box="[141,218,502,528]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="35.[132,143,1895,1912]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@35.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIG. 24. — Sauropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-D, posterior left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG11-837) in labial (A), mesial (B), lingual (C) and distal (D) views; E-H, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R905) in labial (E), mesial (F), lingual (G) and distal (H) views; I-L, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG13-2330) in labial (I), mesial (J), lingual (K) and distal (L) views; M-P, left premaxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-R289) in labial (M), mesial (N), lingual (O) and distal (P) views; Q-T, dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-3495) in labial (Q), mesial (R), lingual (S) and distal (T) views; U-X, left dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14- R435) in labial (U), mesial (V), lingual (W) and distal (X) views; Y-AA, maxillary tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANG R-1732) in labial (Y), distal (Z) and lingual (AA) views. Scale bar: A-X, 2 cm; Y-AA, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902095/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">Figs 24</figureCitation>
Y-AA; 25A). They are spatulate and characterized by straight and subparallel distal and mesial edges at the base of the crown, and by the presence of a convex labial and concave lingual surface. Based on these features, these teeth are assigned to a macronarian sauropod probably close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1877" box="[627,776,630,656]" class="Reptilia" family="Camarasauridae" genus="Camarasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[627,776,630,656]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">Camarasaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="WILSON J. A." box="[142,283,662,688]" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" pagination="215 - 275" part="136" refId="ref50814" refString="WILSON J. A. 2002. - Sauropod dinosaur phylogeny: critique and cladistic analysis. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 136: 215 - 275. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2002.00029. x" title="Sauropod dinosaur phylogeny: critique and cladistic analysis" type="journal article" year="2002">Wilson 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="UPCHURCH P. &amp; BARRETT P. M. &amp; DODSON P." box="[297,527,662,688]" editor="WEISHAMPEL D. B. &amp; DODSON P. &amp; OSMOLSKA H." journalOrPublisher="University of California Press, Berkeley" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" pagination="259 - 322" part="2 nd edition" refId="ref50260" refString="UPCHURCH P., BARRETT P. M. &amp; DODSON P. 2004. - Sauropoda, in WEISHAMPEL D. B., DODSON P. &amp; OSMOLSKA H. (eds), The Dinosauria. 2 nd edition. University of California Press, Berkeley: 259 - 322." title="Sauropoda" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="The Dinosauria" year="2004">
Upchurch 
<emphasis box="[413,464,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mocho" box="[541,739,662,688]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Mocho" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" pagination="259 - 295" refId="ref44419" refString="MOCHO P., ROYO- TORRES R., MALAFAIA E., ESCASO F. &amp; ORTEGA F. 2017. - Sauropod tooth morphotypes from the Upper Jurassic of the Lusitanian basin (Portugal). Papers in Palaeontology 3: 259 - 295. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / spp 2.1075" type="journal article" year="2017">
Mocho 
<emphasis box="[625,677,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[130,776,375,1103]" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">
Sauropod track casts have also been recorded at Angeac- Charente. Thay are represented by casts of pes and manus footprints (
<bibRefCitation author="ROZADA L. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; VULLO R. &amp; AUGIER D. &amp; GOEDERT J. &amp; JEAN A. &amp; ROYO- TORRES R. &amp; QVARNSTROM M. &amp; PEYRE DE FABREGUES C. &amp; MARCHAL J." box="[251,442,757,783]" journalOrPublisher="Lethaia" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" pagination="141 - 165" part="54" refId="ref48377" refString="ROZADA L., ALLAIN R., VULLO R., AUGIER D., GOEDERT J., JEAN A., ROYO- TORRES R., QVARNSTROM M., PEYRE DE FABREGUES C. &amp; MARCHAL J. 2021. - A Lower Cretaceous Lagerstatte from Western Europe: taphonomical overview of the vertebrate assemblage of Angeac-Charente site (Western France). Lethaia 54: 141 - 165. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / let. 12394" title="A Lower Cretaceous Lagerstatte from Western Europe: taphonomical overview of the vertebrate assemblage of Angeac-Charente site (Western France)" type="journal article" year="2021">
Rozada 
<emphasis box="[334,383,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">et al.</emphasis>
2021
</bibRefCitation>
). In 2018, a sauropod footprint cast was observed above and in contact with an 
<emphasis box="[625,692,790,815]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">in-situ</emphasis>
broken sauropod radius. It represents a spectacular “instantaneous” preservation of the action of a sauropod pes or manus crushing a sauropod long bone, and inducing bone modifications (breakage, displacement and reorientation) and sediment deformations (
<bibRefCitation author="ROZADA L. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; VULLO R. &amp; AUGIER D. &amp; GOEDERT J. &amp; JEAN A. &amp; ROYO- TORRES R. &amp; QVARNSTROM M. &amp; PEYRE DE FABREGUES C. &amp; MARCHAL J." box="[233,429,949,975]" journalOrPublisher="Lethaia" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" pagination="141 - 165" part="54" refId="ref48377" refString="ROZADA L., ALLAIN R., VULLO R., AUGIER D., GOEDERT J., JEAN A., ROYO- TORRES R., QVARNSTROM M., PEYRE DE FABREGUES C. &amp; MARCHAL J. 2021. - A Lower Cretaceous Lagerstatte from Western Europe: taphonomical overview of the vertebrate assemblage of Angeac-Charente site (Western France). Lethaia 54: 141 - 165. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / let. 12394" title="A Lower Cretaceous Lagerstatte from Western Europe: taphonomical overview of the vertebrate assemblage of Angeac-Charente site (Western France)" type="journal article" year="2021">
Rozada 
<emphasis box="[318,368,949,975]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="718">et al.</emphasis>
2021
</bibRefCitation>
). The footprints are identified as Sauropoda indet. because of the general circular morphology of the pes, the characteristic tubular metacarpal arrangement of the manus and also the huge size of the prints (
<bibRefCitation author="Carrano &amp; Wilson" firstAuthor="Carrano" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" pagination="564 - 582" refId="ref37605" refString="CARRANO M. T. &amp; WILSON J. A. 2001. - Taxon distributions and the tetrapod track record. Paleobiology 27: 564 - 582. https: // doi. org / cn 2 c 2 m" type="journal article" year="2001">Carrano &amp; Wilson 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="WILSON J. A." box="[287,428,1076,1103]" editor="CURRY ROGERS K. A &amp; WILSON J. A." journalOrPublisher="University of California Press, Berkeley" pageId="37" pageNumber="718" pagination="15 - 49" refId="ref50859" refString="WILSON J. A. 2005. - Overview of Sauropod Phylogeny and Evolution, in CURRY ROGERS K. A. &amp; WILSON J. A. (eds), The Sauropods: Evolution and Paleobiology. University of California Press, Berkeley: 15 - 49." title="Overview of Sauropod Phylogeny and Evolution" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="The Sauropods: Evolution and Paleobiology" year="2005">Wilson 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
